  "chunk_index": 37,
  "summary": "Lynn Marchmont decides to leave her current life to marry David Hunter, despite her reluctance about uprooting herself. Recalling David's earlier explanation that he married her in London to prevent her from hesitating, Lynn travels to Long Willow House during a storm to inform Rolly Claude of her decision.\n\nIn the kitchen, Lynn tells Rolly that she loves David and that there is no longer an \"us.\" Rolly reacts with intense, animalistic fury, expressing resentment over his stagnant life on the farm compared to the adventures Lynn has experienced. He reveals his deep bitterness regarding his past, including watching a friend die in war and seeing a girlfriend leave for military service. Rolly declares that if Lynn will not be his, she will be no one's, and he confesses to having killed two people. He then attempts to strangle Lynn.\n\nHercule Poirot interrupts the assault by coughing at the door. After Rolly releases Lynn, Poirot manages the tense situation by providing Lynn with a cold, wet handkerchief for her throat and instructing Rolly to make coffee. Rolly admits to Poirot that he was attempting to kill Lynn and confirms that he killed Charles Trenton. As David Hunter enters the room, bewildered by Lynn's condition, Poirot maintains control of the group. He instructs everyone to sit and listen as he prepares to speak about crime.",
